The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of leaders of the world's major developed economies, no one can say which of them will be part of the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with the British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, the Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with the German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has lasted for two decades.
By the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be towards convergence, and people appeared to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's has illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking down the stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But in recent times, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are becoming increasingly specific), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such an "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded by Japanese cars. They then began producing these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. However, the reversal of global commodity globalization is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotic engineering and the development of processes such as 3D printing.
Thus, the current critique of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this development is not only a reflection of the slowing growth of trade.
Consumers in wealthy countries are far more comfortable with foreign products; in some cases, they even depend on them. This includes constantly updated electronics and inexpensive "fashion trends," which have become dominant in advanced economies.
Rather than rejecting foreign products, the current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on the issues of obscure tribunals protecting the interests of foreign companies and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
This is followed by the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may perhaps be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from bankrupt and impoverished countries.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people around the world travel each year to advanced nations.
The problem lies in the way we travel.
Today, we are more inclined to experiment quickly and superficially, rather than immerse ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know that they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a more profound foundation of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are unlikely to provide good or even honest service to people who are certainly not going to come back.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat you, and hoteliers lie about their facilities.
In addition, this little game may be interrupted.
On sites where tourism has become a source of foreign income, it also becomes an attractive target for terrorists whose ideology is based on anti-Western resentment.
A few attacks in places like Bali or the tourist complexes of the Red Sea are enough to cause deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies address such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The symbol of modern tourism is a massive cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to replicate all the climates of the world.
Indeed, this ship, over 30 meters long, which the Eiffel Tower contains, features a tropical garden and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus and train companies do the same to ensure their customers' safety, releasing them only for a limited time on a famous site—just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel imposes a constraint on the capacity of local infrastructure.
There is often not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors remain within the boundaries of their pre-planned excursions, encountering only fraudsters who offer them trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
Indigenous people do not appreciate tourist groups gathering around their most beautiful sites.
Nobody feels particularly involved, nor do they have any sense of trust.
One soon begins to feel a certain nostalgia for that time when tourism was associated with long stays and prolonged encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, with the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or even months in former monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
For example, Airbnb can provide a much more attractive experience than a hotel, or even worse, than a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
A short time after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill made the famous gesture of setting up camp at the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance between Britain and the United States by deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's altermondialist populists.
